# Onshape Metadata

Metadata is the **property values** bolted onto every level of a document —
Part Number, Name, Description, Revision, State, Material, plus any custom
properties a company defines. It's the non-geometric data: what a part *is*,
not its shape. The `/metadata` group reads and writes these at four scopes:
**document** (workspace/version), **element** (tab), **part**, and **assembly**.
Geometry lives elsewhere (@onshape/parts, @onshape/partstudios); this group only
touches properties.

## Model

- Scope is chosen by the path tail on the standard `…/d/{did}/{wvm}/{wvmid}` base:
  - `/e` — every element in the document; `/e/{eid}` — one element (tab).
  - `/e/{eid}/p` — every part in an element; `/e/{eid}/{iden}/{pid}` — one part
    (`iden` is the identifier kind, `pid` the part id).
  - `/d/{did}/{wv}/{wvid}` (no `/e`) — the workspace/version itself.
- `{wvm}` is `w`/`v`/`m` (workspace/version/microversion); the bare doc scope uses
  `{wv}` = `w`/`v` only. **Writes (POST) must target a workspace `/w/`** —
  versions/microversions are read-only snapshots.
- Every metadata object is **keyed by `propertyId`**: a property carries a stable
  `propertyId`, a human `name`, the current `value`, an `editable` flag and a
  `propertyType`. You edit by POSTing back only the properties you changed —
  same `propertyId`, new `value`. Configurations matter: most reads/writes take a
  `configuration` query param so the values match a specific variant
  (@onshape/configurations).
- **Metadata categories** group property definitions (e.g. a "Sheet Metal Part"
  category exposing its own custom fields). `/metadatacategory/categoryproperties`
  lists the property definitions for given category ids on an owner.

## Endpoints

| METHOD path | purpose |
|---|---|
| `GET /metadata/d/{did}/{wv}/{wvid}` | metadata for a workspace or version (doc scope) |
| `POST /metadata/d/{did}/{wv}/{wvid}` | update workspace/version metadata |
| `GET /metadata/d/{did}/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e` | metadata for all elements in the document |
| `GET /metadata/d/{did}/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e/{eid}` | metadata for one element (tab) |
| `POST /metadata/d/{did}/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e/{eid}` | update one element's metadata |
| `GET /metadata/d/{did}/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e/{eid}/p` | metadata for all parts in an element |
| `GET /metadata/d/{did}/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e/{eid}/{iden}/{pid}` | metadata for one part |
| `POST /metadata/d/{did}/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e/{eid}/{iden}/{pid}` | update one part's metadata |
| `GET /metadata/d/{did}/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e/{eid}/assembly-debug` | assembly metadata incl. supporting/computed data |
| `GET /metadata/standardcontent/d/{did}/v/{vid}/e/{eid}/p/{pid}` | metadata for a standard-content part |
| `POST /metadata/standardcontent/d/{did}` | update a standard-content part's metadata |
| `GET /metadatacategory/categoryproperties` | property definitions for given metadata categories |

Useful query params (read scopes): `configuration`, `includeComputedProperties`,
`includeComputedAssemblyProperties`, `depth`, `thumbnail`, `inferMetadataOwner`,
`linkDocumentId`.

## Shapes

A single-object GET (element / part / doc / standard part) returns one metadata
object whose `properties[]` are `BTMetadataPropertyInfo` keyed by `propertyId`:

```json
{
  "href": "https://cad.onshape.com/api/v10/metadata/d/.../w/.../e/...",
  "jsonType": "metadata-element",
  "properties": [
    { "propertyId": "57f3fb8efa3416c06701d60d",
      "name": "Name",          "value": "Bracket",  "editable": true,  "propertyType": "STRING" },
    { "propertyId": "57f3fb8efa3416c06701d60f",
      "name": "Part number",   "value": "PN-001",    "editable": true,  "propertyType": "STRING" },
    { "propertyId": "57f3fb8efa3416c06701d611",
      "name": "Material",      "value": { "displayName": "Steel" }, "editable": true, "propertyType": "OBJECT" }
  ],
  "thumbnail": { "...": "..." }
}
```

The list scopes (`/e`, `/e/{eid}/p`) wrap many such objects:
`{ "href", "items": [ {…}, … ], "next", "prev" }` (`BTMetadataElementInfo` /
`BTMetadataPartInfo`).

To **update**, POST back only the changed properties — match `propertyId`, send the
new `value`. The body is a JSON string of the same property shape:

```json
{ "properties": [
    { "propertyId": "57f3fb8efa3416c06701d60f", "value": "PN-002" }
] }
```

The POST response is `{}` (re-GET to confirm). `categoryproperties` returns
`{ "href", "items": [ BTCategoryPropertyInfo{…} ], "next", "previous" }` — the
property *definitions* available for a category.

## Recipe

READ-ONLY. Use the kb2 sample doc; any write must go to a throwaway **scratch**
document of your own, never kb2. Basic auth (`access:secret` over HTTPS, local
testing only — production uses HMAC, see @onshape/auth).

```bash
DID=378e93b0ad360aa043a0220b
WID=09273312fedee7bf3c3482ad
EID=a77918b06d5131918477a269
BASE=https://cad.onshape.com/api/v10
AUTH="$ONSHAPE_ACCESS_KEY:$ONSHAPE_SECRET_KEY"

# read this element's (tab's) metadata
curl -sf -u "$AUTH" -H 'Accept: application/json' \
  "$BASE/metadata/d/$DID/w/$WID/e/$EID?includeComputedProperties=true" \
  -o meta.json

# verify: pull a property's name + value (e.g. the Name property)
python3 - <<'PY'
import json
m = json.load(open("meta.json"))
for p in m["properties"]:
    print(p.get("propertyId"), "|", p.get("name"), "=", p.get("value"))
assert m["properties"], "no properties returned"
PY
```

List every part's metadata in the element (verify at least one part comes back):

```bash
curl -sf -u "$AUTH" -H 'Accept: application/json' \
  "$BASE/metadata/d/$DID/w/$WID/e/$EID/p?includeComputedProperties=true" \
  | python3 -c 'import sys,json; d=json.load(sys.stdin); print(len(d["items"]),"parts"); assert d["items"]'
```

To edit (scratch doc only): POST the changed property back, then re-GET to confirm:

```bash
# SCRATCH ids only — never kb2
curl -sf -u "$AUTH" -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  -X POST "$BASE/metadata/d/$DID/w/$WID/e/$EID" \
  --data '{"properties":[{"propertyId":"<id>","value":"PN-002"}]}'
# confirm
curl -sf -u "$AUTH" "$BASE/metadata/d/$DID/w/$WID/e/$EID" \
  | python3 -c 'import sys,json;[print(p["name"],"=",p["value"]) for p in json.load(sys.stdin)["properties"]]'
```

